  "prompt": "Should I write \"Dear Professors\" or \"Dear Prof. A, Prof. B and Prof. C\", while writing an email to 3 professors?",
  "response": "\"Dear Prof. A, Prof. B, and Prof. C\" is generally the more appropriate and professional option. Here's why:\n\n*   **Personalization:** It shows you've taken the time to address them individually, rather than lumping them together. This can make your email seem more thoughtful and respectful.\n*   **Clarity:** It leaves no ambiguity about who you're addressing.\n*   **Formality:** Using the \"Prof.\" title is standard for academic correspondence.\n\nWhile \"Dear Professors\" is acceptable in some contexts, it's less specific and might come across as slightly generic, especially if you already know their names.\n\n**Therefore, \"Dear Prof. A, Prof. B, and Prof. C\" is the better choice.**\n\n**Important considerations:**\n\n*   **Use their correct titles:** If you know that any of them prefer \"Dr.\" or \"Professor Emeritus,\" use that instead.\n*   **Avoid first names:** Unless they have specifically told you to use their first names, stick to the formal titles.\n*   **Order:** If you know the hierarchy or seniority, list the professors in that order. If you don't know, alphabetical order by last name is a safe choice.\n*   **If you're unsure:** If you're really unsure about titles or names, it's always best to err on the side of formality. \"Dear Professors\" is still acceptable and is a safe option if you prefer.\n",
